---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'coverage-comparison', text: 'Coverage Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'pricing', text: 'Pricing', level: 2 },
  { id: 'network-and-claims', text: 'Network and Claims', level: 2 },
  { id: 'who-should-choose', text: 'Who Should Choose Which', level: 2 },
  { id: 'verdict', text: 'Our Verdict', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'SafetyWing Review', href: '/providers/safetywing' },
  { title: 'Aetna International Review', href: '/providers/aetna-international' },
  { title: 'Best Digital Nomad Insurance', href: '/best/digital-nomad-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best for US Expats', href: '/best/us-expat-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Budget Insurance', href: '/best/budget-expat-insurance' },
];

const coverageColumns = [
  { key: 'feature', header: 'Feature' },
  { key: 'safetywing', header: 'SafetyWing' },
  { key: 'aetna', header: 'Aetna International' },
];

const coverageRows = [
  { feature: 'Product Type', safetywing: 'Travel Medical', aetna: 'Health Insurance' },
  { feature: 'Inpatient Care', safetywing: '$250K limit', aetna: '$1M-$5M' },
  { feature: 'Outpatient Care', safetywing: 'Limited', aetna: 'Comprehensive' },
  { feature: 'Mental Health', safetywing: 'Not covered', aetna: 'Covered' },
  { feature: 'Maternity', safetywing: 'Not covered', aetna: 'Optional' },
  { feature: 'Dental', safetywing: 'Emergency only', aetna: 'Optional' },
  { feature: 'Pre-existing Conditions', safetywing: 'Not covered', aetna: 'Underwritten' },
  { feature: 'US Coverage', safetywing: 'Limited ($50K)', aetna: 'Integrated (1.7M+ providers)' },
  { feature: 'Medical Evacuation', safetywing: '$100K', aetna: 'Included' },
  { feature: 'Routine Care', safetywing: 'Not covered', aetna: 'Covered' },
];

const pricingColumns = [
  { key: 'profile', header: 'Profile' },
  { key: 'safetywing', header: 'SafetyWing' },
  { key: 'aetna', header: 'Aetna International' },
];

const pricingRows = [
  { profile: 'Single, Age 30', safetywing: '$45-55/mo', aetna: '$180-250/mo' },
  { profile: 'Single, Age 45', safetywing: '$80-100/mo', aetna: '$300-400/mo' },
  { profile: 'Couple, Age 35', safetywing: '$90-110/mo', aetna: '$360-500/mo' },
  { profile: 'Family of 4', safetywing: '$150-200/mo', aetna: '$600-850/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="SafetyWing vs Aetna International"
  description="Compare SafetyWing and Aetna International. Budget nomad travel medical vs premium US-integrated health insurance."
  headline="SafetyWing vs Aetna International: Nomad Budget vs Premium Coverage"
  subheadline="Fundamentally different products at very different price points. Here's what you're actually getting."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/compare/safetywing-vs-aetna-hero-bg.png"
  heroImage="/images/pages/provider-card-generic.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Quotes from Both"
  ctaButtonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
>
    <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>
  <p>
    SafetyWing and Aetna International are both popular choices for international health insurance, but they serve different needs. Understanding their key differences will help you choose the right coverage for your situation abroad.
  </p>
  <p>
    SafetyWing is a modern insurance option designed specifically for digital nomads and remote workers. Their main subscription-based model with no long-term commitment required. They're particularly popular among digital nomads, remote workers, and location-independent professionals, with very affordable monthly subscription starting around $40/month.
  </p>
  <p>
    Aetna International is backed by CVS Health, offering plans designed for globally mobile individuals. They're known for their integration with US healthcare system and strong employer-sponsored options. They tend to attract US-based companies with international employees and American expats, offering mid-range pricing with good corporate plan options.
  </p>
  <p>
    This comparison breaks down the key differences between these two providers so you can make an informed decision. We'll cover coverage options, pricing estimates, network access, claims processes, and help you determine which one makes more sense for your specific needs and budget.
  </p>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">SafetyWing</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li>Travel medical insurance</li>
        <li>Budget-friendly ($45-55/mo)</li>
        <li>Emergency and acute care focus</li>
        <li>Popular with digital nomads</li>
        <li>Flexible subscription model</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Aetna International</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li>Comprehensive health insurance</li>
        <li>Premium pricing ($180-250/mo)</li>
        <li>Full healthcare coverage</li>
        <li>US network (1.7M+ providers)</li>
        <li>Mental health and maternity options</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Understand Your Options"
    description="Get quotes from both to see the actual price difference for your needs."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="coverage-comparison">Coverage Comparison</h2>
  <p>
    The coverage gap reflects the fundamental difference between travel medical and health insurance.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={coverageColumns} rows={coverageRows} />
  </div>

  <p>
    <strong>Key differences:</strong>
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Product type:</strong> SafetyWing is travel medical (emergencies); Aetna is health insurance (comprehensive care)</li>
    <li><strong>Pre-existing conditions:</strong> SafetyWing excludes them entirely; Aetna can cover with underwriting</li>
    <li><strong>Mental health:</strong> Not covered by SafetyWing; included with Aetna</li>
    <li><strong>Routine care:</strong> SafetyWing doesn't cover checkups or preventive care; Aetna does</li>
    <li><strong>US coverage:</strong> SafetyWing has a $50K cap with limited providers; Aetna has full access to 1.7M+ providers</li>
    <li><strong>Limits:</strong> SafetyWing caps at $250K total; Aetna offers $1M-$5M</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="pricing">Pricing</h2>
  <p>
    SafetyWing costs roughly 75% less than Aetna International. The price difference reflects vastly different coverage levels.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={pricingColumns} rows={pricingRows} />
  </div>

  <p>
    <strong>Notes on pricing:</strong>
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>SafetyWing's low price reflects limited coverage scope</li>
    <li>Aetna's premium buys comprehensive, ongoing healthcare</li>
    <li>SafetyWing has no deductible for most services (small copays instead)</li>
    <li>Aetna offers deductible options to reduce premiums</li>
    <li>The 4x price difference comes with 4x+ more coverage</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="What's the Right Investment?"
    description="Your health needs determine whether budget or premium makes sense."
    buttonText="Get a Quote"
    buttonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
  />

  <h2 id="network-and-claims">Network and Claims</h2>

  <h3>Provider Networks</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Aetna International</strong> provides access to Aetna's massive US network (1.7M+ providers) plus international coverage. Direct billing is common and straightforward.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>SafetyWing</strong> works primarily on reimbursement. Some hospitals may direct bill, but you'll often pay upfront and claim back. The US network is limited.
  </p>

  <h3>Claims Process</h3>
  <p>
    Aetna has an established healthcare infrastructure with polished digital tools. SafetyWing's process is simpler—submit receipts online—but may require more upfront payment.
  </p>

  <h3>Customer Support</h3>
  <p>
    Aetna offers comprehensive support with established customer service. SafetyWing provides chat-based support suited to their tech-savvy nomad audience.
  </p>

  <h2 id="who-should-choose">Who Should Choose Which</h2>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Choose SafetyWing If:</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li>You're a healthy digital nomad</li>
        <li>You only need emergency coverage</li>
        <li>Budget is your primary concern</li>
        <li>You have no pre-existing conditions</li>
        <li>You don't need mental health or maternity</li>
        <li>You're comfortable with coverage gaps</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Choose Aetna International If:</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li>You're a US citizen abroad</li>
        <li>You need comprehensive healthcare</li>
        <li>You have pre-existing conditions</li>
        <li>Mental health coverage matters</li>
        <li>You return to the US regularly</li>
        <li>You want true health insurance, not travel coverage</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="verdict">Our Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    This isn't really an apples-to-apples comparison—it's apples to oranges.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>SafetyWing</strong> serves a specific need well: affordable emergency coverage for healthy nomads who accept limited benefits. If you're young, healthy, have no pre-existing conditions, and just need a safety net for accidents or acute illness, SafetyWing delivers reasonable value.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Aetna International</strong> is actual health insurance. It covers ongoing healthcare needs, mental health, potential maternity, pre-existing conditions, and integrates seamlessly with US healthcare. The premium is 4x higher because you get dramatically more coverage.
  </p>
  <p>
    The question isn't which is "better"—it's what you actually need. Emergency coverage for a healthy 28-year-old? SafetyWing works. Comprehensive healthcare for an expat with any complexity? Aetna is the appropriate choice.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Decide?"
    description="Compare quotes to see the actual difference for your situation."
    buttonText="Compare Plans Now"
    buttonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This comparison is for informational purposes only. Prices, coverage, and plan details change. We are not insurance brokers. Verify all information with the providers before purchasing.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
